{
  "slug": "the-adam-sandler-hall-of-fame-and-jay-kelly-with-noah-baumba",
  "title": "The Adam Sandler Hall of Fame and ‘Jay Kelly’ With Noah Baumbach!",
  "show": "The Big Picture",
  "network": "The Ringer",
  "hosts": [
    "Sean Fennessey",
    "Amanda Dobbins"
  ],
  "published": "2025-12-10",
  "runtimeMin": 145,
  "format": "Sean Fennessey and Amanda Dobbins spend the first hour arguing over Noah Baumbach's 'Jay Kelly': Sean thinks it's a mess he wishes he loved, Amanda likes it with notes. Then they build a ten-slot Adam Sandler Hall of Fame by walking his whole filmography green, yellow, or red. The Hanukkah Song takes a slot without being a film. Baumbach closes the show, talking to Sean about movie stardom, getting something desperate out of Sandler, and the six years since 'Marriage Story.'",
  "segments": [
    {
      "kind": "review",
      "heading": "‘Jay Kelly’",
      "note": "Sean saw it twice; Amanda's the inverse of him on it",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Jay Kelly",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Sean fought his way to the Venice premiere and has now seen it twice; he thinks it's 'a real mess' he wants to like more, because the movie-star/daughters thread and the Jay/Ron manager thread never fuse and the farce keeps undercutting the sadness. Amanda's the inverse: the family melodrama is the weaker, un-Baumbachian half, while the film works whenever people talk about the 'empty vessel' star rather than when he talks. Both love Sandler as Ron (heartbreaking), and rate the family-therapy scene, the woods scene with Riley Keough, and Billy Crudup's menu monologue; both are cooler on the train set piece and the cinema-tribute ending, and both catch the daughters aging inconsistency. Clooney maybe very good. Shot by Linus Sandgren, scored by Nicholas Britell, co-written with Emily Mortimer, and in conversation with 'Sentimental Value.'"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "halloffame",
      "heading": "The Adam Sandler Hall of Fame",
      "honoree": "Adam Sandler",
      "note": "ten slots; The Hanukkah Song takes one without being a film, so nine movies get in",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Billy Madison",
          "year": 1995,
          "role": "Billy Madison",
          "note": "'Incredibly green.' The 26-year-old heir who repeats grades one through twelve a week at a time. Sean singles out the James Downey principal/trivia scene opposite Bradley Whitford as one of '10 or 12 moments of extremely special shit.' Non-negotiable, even though it and Happy Gilmore 'represent the same thing.' They just like them both."
        },
        {
          "title": "Happy Gilmore",
          "year": 1996,
          "role": "Happy Gilmore",
          "note": "A Happy Gilmore year, with the sequel out and named Craig Horlbeck's favorite of 2025. Not a huge box-office hit at the time but a VHS/video-store staple that set Sandler on his way. In on the same instinct as Billy Madison."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Wedding Singer",
          "year": 1998,
          "role": "Robbie Hart",
          "note": "Auto-green. The movie that changed the trajectory of his career and proved he could be a heartthrob, with real chemistry opposite Drew Barrymore. Amanda's caveat: it's the reflexive answer whenever you ask a man his favorite rom-com. Also stands in for 50 First Dates."
        },
        {
          "title": "Big Daddy",
          "year": 1999,
          "role": "Sonny Koufax",
          "note": "Sandler going more grounded, with real notes of drama in the bond with the kid played by the Sprouse twins. Sean greens it partly to 'live in it' with his friends, and because it's lived on; Jon Stewart and Leslie Mann in support."
        },
        {
          "title": "Punch-Drunk Love",
          "year": 2002,
          "role": "Barry Egan",
          "note": "Green. Paul Thomas Anderson saw that Sandler's anger could be redirected into a sad character study that becomes a romance, the whole duality of the persona. Yelling at Philip Seymour Hoffman down the phone; the little dance in the SnackWell's aisle."
        },
        {
          "title": "Funny People",
          "year": 2009,
          "role": "George Simmons",
          "note": "Judd Apatow; an established comic pulling in a younger one (Seth Rogen), and both their emptinesses. Has made a comeback as underrated-but-good, still too long; Sean compares it to Jay Kelly. Started yellow, pushed to green."
        },
        {
          "title": "Grown Ups",
          "year": 2010,
          "role": "Lenny Feder",
          "note": "Jack Sanders pounded the pavement for it. The highest-grossing live-action non-Dracula Sandler movie, and the slot stands in for the whole Blended / Just Go with It / Bedtime Stories dad-comedy box-office era: a guy who could still draw hundreds of millions just goofing off with his buddies."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Meyerowitz Stories",
          "year": 2017,
          "role": "Danny Meyerowitz",
          "note": "'Wonderful.' His first Netflix film and first with Baumbach, with great singing and dynamic scenes opposite Dustin Hoffman and Grace Van Patten. Chosen over Jay Kelly on the '25-for-25, only one Baumbach allowed' rule; Sean thinks he has more to do here."
        },
        {
          "title": "Uncut Gems",
          "year": 2019,
          "role": "Howard Ratner",
          "note": "'Green, green, green.' The gambler who can't quit. A now-beyond-cult classic that somehow missed the 2019 awards. The Safdie energy that baffled the 65-year-olds at the Telluride premiere is now part of the grammar."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "interview",
      "heading": "Noah Baumbach on ‘Jay Kelly’",
      "guest": "Noah Baumbach on",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Jay Kelly",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Baumbach on co-writing with Emily Mortimer, the dreamlike memory language that expands as the film goes (Jay walks into his own flashbacks and eventually speaks in them), hiring Linus Sandgren, and getting something needy and 'destroyed' out of Sandler, whom he calls a shadow version of Clooney's Jay. Peter's plea to Jay draws on his closeness with Peter Bogdanovich. He sees the film as an elegy for a kind of movie stardom, and worries we make too little for new stars to reveal themselves."
        },
        {
          "title": "White Noise",
          "year": 2022,
          "note": "He's proud of it but 'didn't have a good time making it,' shot during COVID; thinks it got read as a COVID movie nobody wanted to sit with, and hopes it gets another look. Working on Barbie with Greta Gerwig 'brought him back' to loving filmmaking after that shoot."
        },
        {
          "title": "Small Change",
          "year": 1976,
          "note": "His last-great-thing: Truffaut's 'Small Change,' which he and Greta Gerwig projected and then talked about for days. 'As good as The 400 Blows,' and a rebuke to the idea that '70s Truffaut was selling out."
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
